{The Italian Game is one of the oldest and most natural openings. White develops quickly toward the center and kingside.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game. White targets f7 and prepares to castle.} Bc5 {The Giuoco Piano — the "quiet game".} (3... Nf6 {The Two Knights Defense — sharper and more tactical.} 4. d4 (4. Ng5 {The Fried Liver Attack direction.} d5 5. exd5 Na5 {The main line. Black gives up a pawn for rapid development.}) exd4 5. O-O Nxe4 {Black grabs the center pawn.} (5... Bc5 {The Max Lange Attack.} 6. e5 d5 7. exf6 dxc4)) 4. c3 {The Giuoco Piano proper. White prepares d4.} (4. d3 {The Giuoco Pianissimo — very quiet, slow buildup.} Nf6 5. O-O d6 6. c3 O-O) (4. b4 {The Evans Gambit! White sacrifices a pawn for rapid development.} Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 (5... Be7 {The defensive retreat.} 6. d4 Na5) 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O {White has a huge lead in development for one pawn.}) Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 (7. Nc3 {The main alternative.} Nxe4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 d5) Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 d5 {Black strikes back in the center.} *
